 with the Enlightenment era belief that fatness was evidence of "savagery" and racial inferiority. The author argues that the contemporary ideal of slenderness is, at its very core, racialized and racist. Indeed, it was not until the early twentieth century, when racialized attitudes against fatness were already entrenched in the culture, that the medical establishment began its crusade against obesity. An important and original work, Fearing the Black Body argues convincingly that fat phobia isn't about health at all, but rather a means of using the body to validate race, class, and gender prejudice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Okt 2020) 0aAfrican American womenxSocial conditions. 0aFeminine beauty (Aesthetics)xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aObesityxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aOverweight womenzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 4aAmerican exceptionalism. 4aAryan supremacy. 4aBritish history. 4aEnlightenment. 4aJohn Harvey Kellogg. 4aProtestantism. 4aPuritanism. 4aRenaissance art. 4abeauty. 4ablackness. 4abody mass index. 4adiets. 4aembodiment. 4aethnic studies. 4aeugenics. 4afat stigma. 4afat studies. 4ahealth disparities. 4ahistory of medicine. 4ahistory of science. 4aimmigration. 4aobesity. 4arace. 4aracism. 4aslavery. 4asociology of medicine. 4athin ideal. 4awhiteness. 4awomen's history. 4awomen's studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071028140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479891788423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479891788.jpg  a978-3-11-071028-1  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV